5-FU needs to be transported into the cells and perform its function by diffusion or highly binding with nucleobase carrier. It is metabolized through anabolic and catabolic pathways. In the anabolic route, with the involvement of thymidine phosphorylase (TP), uridine phosphorylase (UP), uridine kinase (UK), orotate phosphribosyl transferase (OPRT) and phosphoribosyl pyrophosphate (PRPP), 5-FU is converted to active metabolites, such as fluorouridine triphosphate (FUTP), fluorouridine diphosphate (FUDP), FUDP-sugars, fluorodeoxyuridine monophosphate (FdUMP).

TS mRNA level was increased in 5-FU resistant CRC cells. Elevated TS expression was reported to be associated with poor OS rate in patients with mCRC. Acquired 5-FU resistance is identified to be correlated with TS gene amplification and mutations.

DPD inhibition, on the other hand, has been shown to re-sensitize CRC to 5-FU both in vitro and in vivo, indicating that interference of DPD could be an approach to overcome 5-FU resistance.

TP catalyzes the conversion of 5-FU to its active form, 5-fluoro-2â²-deoxyuridine. It has been reported that elevated TP expression is a promising phenotype for 5-FU response and is correlated with prolonged PFS in CRC patients.

Irinotecan inhibits DNA TOP 1, resulting in misalignment and therefore inhibiting DNA replication and transcription. Irinotecan can be activated by carboxylesterase 1/2 (CES1/2) and catalyzed to a more active metabolite SN-38, both of which could form an inhibitory complex with TOP1 and DNA.

CYP3A4/5 catalyze the degradation of irinotecan. It has been found that an increase in CYP3A4/5 activity or a decrease in CES1/2 activity is correlated with irinotecan resistance.

UGT1As can glucuronidate SN-38 and form an inactive SN-38 glucuronide. Therefore, the genetic polymorphisms of UGT1A have also been related to irinotecan resistance.

Oxaliplatin is a platinum DNA alkylating reagent widely used in CRC treatment. It has been shown that oxaliplatin could present a cross-resistance with cisplatin and carboplatin.

Thio-containing molecules, such as glutathione (GSH), have been found to form conjugates with platinum compounds, thereby blocking their activity.

Decreased GSH level was found to enhance oxaliplatin sensitivity.

Apoptosis is a programmed cell death process. It is a homeostatic mechanism to maintain the cell population. Bcl-2, a well-established apoptosis marker, has been shown to promote CRC progression and treatment resistance.

Mcl-1, a pro-survival member of the Bcl-2 protein family, has been reported to confer chemoresistance by translocating to the nucleus.

IAPs are also critical for CRC treatment resistance. Cellular IAP1 and IAP2 could contribute to the tumor necrosis factor-alpha (TNF-Î±) induced nuclear factor kappa-B (NF-ÎºB) activation and therefore promote cell proliferation.

XIAP could inhibit apoptosis by suppressing caspase3/7 and caspase-9.

Chemotherapies induce apoptosis by upregulating tumor suppression genes such as p53 (TP53). However, up to 60% of CRC patients harbor the mutated p53, which has been reported to be associated with poor prognosis and chemotherapy resistance.

Autophagy is a catabolic process in which cellular organelles are degraded while the constituent metabolites are recycled to promote cell survival.

Beclin-1 and Ras-related in brain 7 (Rab-7) have been correlated with treatment resistance and poor survival.

IL-6 in the tumor microenvironment (TME) has also been identified to trigger autophagy via the JAK2/BECN1 pathway.

Ferroptosis is a unique pattern of cell death hallmarked by iron-dependent phospholipid peroxidation.

Lipocalin 2, an iron homeostasis-regulating protein, is overexpressed in CRC and related to 5-FU treatment resistance.

Nrf2 is a key regulator that plays pivotal roles in lipid peroxidation.

Nrf2 regulated heme oxygenase-1 (HO-1) activation could promote 5-FU treatment resistance in CRC.

TME is composed of various infiltrated tumor-associated cells and the cytokines secreted by those cells.

Cancer-associated fibroblasts (CAF) have been identified to promote CRC resistance and relapse in multiple ways.

Proteomic analysis has revealed that CAF-derived C-C motif chemokine ligand 2 (CCL-2) induced the upregulation of FGFR4 expression in CRC cells.

Elevated FGFR4 accumulation activates the Î²-catenin pathway, further contributing to the 5-FU and oxaliplatin resistance.

. Cancer germline antigens, also known as cancer-testis (CT) antigens, are the products of genes normally expressed by gametes and trophoblasts only; these genes are epigenetically silenced in adult tissues but are aberrantly expressed in a range of cancers (reviewed in [

TP53
mutations are more frequent and appear to be a key driver of acquired drug resistance in advanced cancer patients.

TP53
mutations are heterogeneous and are known to induce complex transcriptional changes effecting multiple biological responses.

TP53
mutations are divided into 2 categories: structural mutants, where protein folding is altered and DNA-contact mutants, where changes in critical amino acids affect DNA binding.

TP53
mutations are spread across the DNA binding domain (DBD) in lung cancer, clustered toward the c-terminal end of the DBD in the colon, and clustered more in the middle of the DBD in breast and ovarian cancer.

TP53
mutations in exon 4 affect transactivation, while mutations in exon 5, 6, and 7 are buried within the p53 structure and affect DNA binding.

TP53
mutations in exon 5 (lung cancer) and two mutations in exon 7 (colon cancer) affect zinc binding, while exon 8 mutations partially expose DNA binding.

TP53
mutations away from DNA and proteinâprotein interaction sites enhance structural disruption of the p53 protein that dysregulate affinity of binding to DNA targets.

TP53
mutations may be truncal or acquired at metastatic sites.

TP53
mutations may partner with unique co-mutations in colon and lung cancer.

TP53
mutations are enriched at both primary and metastatic sites, indicating both truncal and acquired mutations.

TP53
mutations may activate unique signaling pathways within a background of epistasis.

TP53
mutations may be targeted with small molecule inhibitors APR-246, PRIMA-1, and MDM2 inhibitor AMG 232.

TP53
mutations may be targeted with PARP inhibitors, mTOR inhibitors, and histone lysine methyltransferase inhibitors.

TP53
mutations may upregulate the activation of specific cellular pathways that can be investigated by whole genome transcription assays.

TP53
mutations may drive unique signaling pathways that can be targeted with rational therapies.

TP53
mutations may differ based on specific mutations and tumor type, thus multi-mutant, multi-omics strategies are needed to elucidate cancer protecting activities that can be targeted.

TP53
mutations may be used to develop transcriptional models to identify signaling pathway drivers.

TP53
mutations may be used to develop unique clinical trials personalized to each patientâs malignancy.

TP53
mutations may be used to assess targetable and non-targetable genomic aberrations and provide a handle on moving the needle to enhance survival in patients with metastatic disease.

TP53
mutations are more frequent in lung (80%), colon = pancreas (75%), CUPS (63%), and breast (41%) cancers.

TP53
mutations are not detected in the rectum, anus, appendix, and melanoma.

TP53
mutations are variable with most affecting the central DNA-binding core domain and to a lesser degree the C-terminal domain that down-regulates DNA binding to the central domain and the acidic N-terminus transcription-activation domain.

TP53
mutations may track with unique co-mutations that orchestrate distinct transcriptional programs and signaling pathways.

TP53
mutations may be conserved in both primary and metastatic sites, while new mutations are acquired in metastatic samples.

TP53
mutations may result in the loss of wild-type function which exerts dominant-negative regulatory effects over co-expressed wild-type p53.

TP53
mutations may be oncogenic in ways not related to those associated with wild type p53 functions.

TP53
mutations may be associated with cell invasion, migration, scattering, survival, proliferation, angiogenesis, stem cell expansion, and tissue remodeling.

TP53
mutations may be associated with distinct non-actionable mutations that drive unique signaling pathways.

TP53
mutations may be associated with a paucity of universal mutations limited to metastatic sites.

mutations may be associated with a lack of knowledge of these signaling pathways.
